\subsection{Summarising commits for listing}

The [[list]] command (\cref{sec:list-command}) needs a compact
one-line summary of each commit: the command that was run, when it
started, and how many runs the commit contains.
All of this information lives in the commit message body, so we
parse it here rather than making additional Git calls.

We split the message on the block separator to count runs, then
extract the command from the first [[Run:]] line and the start
time from the first [[Start-Time:]] field.
The function returns [[None]] when the message contains no run
blocks---this happens for the initial commit or when all runs
have been filtered out.

<<commit data functions>>=
def parse_run_summary(message):
    """Extract a summary from a commit message body.

    Returns ``(command, start_time, run_count)`` where
    ``command`` is the script and arguments string,
    ``start_time`` is formatted as ``YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM``,
    and ``run_count`` is the number of run blocks.
    Returns ``None`` if the message contains no runs.
    """
    if not message or not message.strip():
        return None

    blocks = message.split(BLOCK_SEP)
    run_blocks = [
        b for b in blocks
        if b.strip().startswith("Run:")
    ]
    if not run_blocks:
        return None

    <<extract command from first run block>>
    <<extract start time from first run block>>

    return (command, start_time, len(run_blocks))
@

The first line of a run block is [[Run: script args]]---the same
text that [[git log --oneline]] shows as the commit subject.
We strip the [[Run: ]] prefix to recover the command string as
the student typed it.

<<extract command from first run block>>=
first = run_blocks[0].strip()
first_line = first.split("\n", 1)[0]
command = first_line[len("Run: "):]
@

The [[Start-Time:]] field sits in the same first run block
([[first]]) parsed above.
Its value is an ISO\,8601 timestamp that we reformat to a
human-friendly [[YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM]] since full ISO timestamps
are noisy in a compact listing.

<<extract start time from first run block>>=
start_time = ""
for line in first.split("\n"):
    if line.startswith("Start-Time:"):
        iso = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
        try:
            dt = datetime.datetime.fromisoformat(iso)
            start_time = dt.strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")
        except ValueError:
            start_time = iso
        break
@

Let's verify the summary extraction for single runs, multiple
runs, and empty messages:

<<test functions>>=
def test_parse_run_summary_single_run():
    from learnlog.cli import parse_run_summary
    msg = (
        "Run: hello.py arg1 arg2\n"
        "\n"
        "Script: hello.py\n"
        "Arguments: arg1 arg2\n"
        "Start-Time: 2026-03-20T14:30:00"
    )
    result = parse_run_summary(msg)
    assert result is not None
    command, start_time, count = result
    assert command == "hello.py arg1 arg2"
    assert start_time == "2026-03-20 14:30"
    assert count == 1

def test_parse_run_summary_multiple_runs():
