\section{ProgSnap2 export}
\label{sec:progsnap2}

ProgSnap2 is a standardised data format for programming process
data, developed by the CS education community
(\url{https://cssplice.org/progsnap2/}).
It captures how students write code over time---exactly what
learnlog records---but in a format that analysis tools can consume
directly.

A ProgSnap2 dataset is a zip file containing:
\begin{description}
\item[DatasetMetadata.csv] Version and configuration fields.
\item[MainTable.csv] One row per event (file edits, program runs).
\item[CodeStates/] A directory of source file snapshots, one
  subdirectory per unique code state.
\end{description}

We use the \texttt{.progsnap2} extension to distinguish these
files from Git bundles.

<<constants>>=
DEFAULT_PROGSNAP2_NAME = "learnlog.progsnap2"
PROGSNAP2_VERSION = 8
@


\subsection{Parsing individual run blocks}

The existing [[parse_run_summary]] (\cref{sec:export}) extracts
just enough for the [[list]] command: command string, start time,
and run count.
ProgSnap2 needs every field from every run block---exit code,
end time, exception type, I/O---so we need a more thorough parser.

A run block has two parts: a \emph{header} written by
[[begin_run]] (always present) and a \emph{trailer} written by
[[finalize_run]] (missing if the program was killed by SIGKILL).
The header contains [[Run:]], [[Script:]], [[Arguments:]], and
[[Start-Time:]]; the trailer contains [[End-Time:]],
[[Exit-Code:]], [[--- I/O ---]], and [[--- exception ---]].

We parse each block into a flat dict with string values, keeping
the raw text for I/O and exception sections.  Missing trailer
fields are represented as [[None]]---this lets callers distinguish
\enquote{program crashed} from \enquote{exit code was zero}.

<<export functions>>=
def parse_run_block(block_text):
    """Parse a single run block into a dict.

    Returns a dict with keys ``script``, ``arguments``,
    ``start_time``, ``end_time``, ``exit_code``,
    ``io_log``, and ``exception_info``.
    Missing trailer fields are ``None``.
    """
    result = {
        "script": None, "arguments": None,
        "start_time": None, "end_time": None,
        "exit_code": None, "io_log": None,
        "exception_info": None,
    }

    <<parse header fields>>
    <<parse trailer fields>>

    return result
@

The header fields are simple key--value pairs, one per line.
We skip the first [[Run:]] line because it duplicates the
[[Script:]] and [[Arguments:]] fields in a less structured form.

<<parse header fields>>=
for line in block_text.split("\n"):
    if line.startswith("Script:"):
        result["script"] = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
    elif line.startswith("Arguments:"):
        result["arguments"] = (
            line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
        )
    elif line.startswith("Start-Time:"):
        result["start_time"] = (
            line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
        )
    elif line.startswith("End-Time:"):
        result["end_time"] = (
            line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
        )
    elif line.startswith("Exit-Code:"):
        result["exit_code"] = (
            line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
        )
@

The I/O and exception sections use [[--- I/O ---]] and
[[--- exception ---]] as delimiters.
We extract the text between these markers, treating [[None]] and
[[(no I/O)]] as empty values.

<<parse trailer fields>>=
if "--- I/O ---" in block_text:
    io_start = block_text.index("--- I/O ---")
    io_text = block_text[io_start + len("--- I/O ---"):]
    if "--- exception ---" in io_text:
        exc_marker = io_text.index("--- exception ---")
        io_content = io_text[:exc_marker].strip()
        exc_content = io_text[
            exc_marker + len("--- exception ---"):
        ].strip()
        if io_content and io_content != "(no I/O)":
            result["io_log"] = io_content
        if exc_content and exc_content != "None":
            result["exception_info"] = exc_content
    else:
        io_content = io_text.strip()
        if io_content and io_content != "(no I/O)":
            result["io_log"] = io_content
@

Let's verify the parser handles complete blocks, header-only
blocks (crash), and blocks with exceptions:

